\title{P vs. NP}
\author{Daniel Uribe}

\maketitle


\tableofcontents



\cleardoublepage


\chapter{Problem Statement}
\section{Introduction}

\begin{par}
Given a set of inputs and an algorithm, how many operations does it take for the algorithm to terminate?  This is the question at the heart of algorithm analysis and the essence of the question of \textbf{P} $\overset{?}{=}$ \textbf{NP}.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
Computer scientists and software engineers study a variety of problems as well as a handful of solutions.  The more nascent the programmer, the more trivial the problem.  After ``hello world'', the first assignment given to undergraduates in the subject is typically a sorting problem.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
Given an array of integers as input, write a function which will return the same set of numbers in ascending order.  Example input $[ 10, 5, 27, 1 ]$.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
To an experienced programmer leveraging a high level language, the problem reduces to a call to the language's built-in sort routine.  However, to the inexperienced programmer, either unaware of the built in functionality or forbidden from using it, this is a very humbling problem.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
My approach, when initially given this problem with a set of 10 numbers, was a method known as bubble sort.  The algorithm is simple to conceive and relatively easy to implement:
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\pagebreak

\begin{par}
\begin{algorithmic}
	\STATE {\textbf{var} } inputArray = [ 10, 5, 27, 1 ];
	\STATE {\textbf{var} } index = 1;
	\WHILE{index $<$ inputArray.Length}
		\STATE {\textbf{var} } a = inputArray[index - 1];
		\STATE {\textbf{var} } b = inputArray[index];
		\IF{b $<$ a}
			\STATE inputArray[index - 1] = b;
			\STATE inputArray[index] = a;
			\STATE index = 1;
		\ELSE
			\STATE index++;
		\ENDIF
	\ENDWHILE
\end{algorithmic}
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
At first, there is an aura of greatness felt by an individual able to write a program without an infinite loop.  However, once this aura fades and the input set gets larger, one must ask, ``how long is this supposed to take?''
\end{par} \vspace{1em}


\subsection{Definition of \textbf{P}}

\begin{par}
A language $L$ is in \textbf{P} if and only if there exists a deterministic Turing machine $M$, such that
\begin{enumerate}
	\item $M$ runs for polynomial time on all inputs;

	\item $\forall \, x \in L, M$ outputs 1; and

	\item $\forall \, x \notin L, M$ outputs 0.

\end{enumerate}
\end{par} \vspace{1em}


\subsubsection{Understanding \textbf{P}}

\begin{par}
This language is a bit unwieldy, so let us simplify the terminology a bit.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
The deterministic Turing machine $M$ can be thought of as any PC in the world.  Here, deterministic implies that under identical conditions, the program will always execute the same set of instructions and output the same result.  This is what we generally assume to be the case when we run a program.  For example, a calculator asked to add $2 + 2$ will always output $4$, rather than some random number.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
The language $L$ represents what we typically think of a program, but with the added restriction that it may answer only ``yes'' or ``no'' to whatever question it is asked.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
While sorting is not immediately a ``yes'' or ``no'' question, it may be morphed into one by asking the language $L$ (i.e. the program), ``if I give you this array of integers, is it possible for you to sort it?''  Any mathematician would respond by stating that the integers are a totally ordered set, so this question should always be answered in constant time.  While true, especially for mathematicians, a computer must evaluate the input before it can state ``yes'' or ``no'' (i.e. 1 or 0).
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
With this understanding of \textbf{P}, we can now establish a worst case runtime for bubble sort.  The input requiring maximal position swap operations is an array which is sorted in descending order.  For a computer to answer the ``is sortable'' question, it must:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item test array elements $a_0, a_1$ at positions 0 and 1 (resp.);

	\item  swap array positions 0 and 1, i.e. $a_0 \to$ position 1 and $a_1 \to$ position 0;

	\item test array elements $a_1, a_0$ at positions 0 and 1 (resp.);

	\item test array elements $a_0, a_2$ at positions 1 and 2 (resp.);

	\item swap array positions 1 and 2, i.e. $a_0 \to$ position 2 and $a_2 \to$ position 1;

	\item test array positions $a_1, a_2$ at positions 0 and 1 (resp.);

	\item swap array positions 0 and 1, i.e. $a_1 \to$ position 1 and $a_2 \to$ position 0;

	\item $\ldots.$

\end{enumerate}
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
Ultimately, the $0^{\textnormal{th}}$ and $1^{\textnormal{st}}$ elements are swapped $n - 1$ times.  The $1^{\textnormal{st}}$ and $2^{\textnormal{nd}}$ elements are swapped $n-2$ times and so on, until finally the $(n-2)^{\textnormal{nd}}$ and $(n-1)^{\textnormal{st}}$ elements are swapped just once.  This totals $n \cdot (n - 1) / 2$ operations, as seen by

nexttext:
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
Additionally, for every swap, there is a corresponding comparison of adjacent elements which does not result in a swap.  These additional tests double the total number of operations relevant to the algorithm,

\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
Worst case runtime is an analysis of asymptotic behavior, i.e. how the execution time of the program scales as $n \to \infty$.  Even though bubble sort is $n$ operations ``better than'' an algorithm that executes $n^2$ operations, the execution time of the program still scales on the order of $n^2$.  That is, if it takes 10 seconds to sort an array of 1 million elements ($n = 10^6$), then sorting 2 million elements ($2 \cdot n$) will take $\sim 40$ seconds to execute.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
The notation for this asymptotic behavior is $O(n^2)$ (pronounced ``big-Oh'' of $n^2$).  Since, both $n^2 - n$ and $n^2$ are polynomials, bubble sort is said to be in \textbf{P}.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
Two important questions:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item is it possible to do better? (yes)

	\item is it possible to do worse? (yes)
\end{enumerate}
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
A \textbf{comparison based algorithm}, or \textbf{flow control based algorithm}, is an algorithm which makes execution path decisions based on the result of a comparison, for example $b < a$.  As we will show, the best possible runtime for a flow control based sorting algorithm is $\Omega (n \cdot \log n)$.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
The worst possible runtime is that the program never terminates.  The set of problems for which the best algorithms never halt is not a terribly fun branch of computer science to study.  So, let us move on to a more interesting complexity class.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}


\subsection{Definition of \textbf{NP}}

\begin{par}
A language $L$ is in \textbf{NP} if and only if there exist polynomials $p$ and $q$, and a deterministic Turing machine $M$, such that
\begin{enumerate}
	\item $\forall \, x, y$, the machine $M$ runs in time $p(|x|)$ on input $(x,y)$;

	\item $\forall \, x \in L, \, \exists$ a string $y$ of length $q(|x|)$ such that $M(x,y) = 1$;

	\item $\forall \, x \notin L$ and all strings $y$ of length $q(|x|)$, $M(x,y) = 0$.

\end{enumerate}
\end{par} \vspace{1em}



\subsubsection{Understanding \textbf{NP}}

\begin{par}
Again, let us translate from the formal definition to a more intuitive interpretation.  \textbf{NP} is the class of problems which may be checked in polynomial time on a deterministic Turing machine.  The non-deterministic part of \textbf{NP} is the input string $y$, which is an answer provided as an input to the program by some ``oracle''.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
The definition is obfuscated by the fact that we are given two variables as input, $(x,y)$, but the runtime $p(|x|)$ requires just the one variable $x$.  The variable $y$ is required as an input because we are executing a test.  In the example of the clique problem, this test will be an equality comparison between two bit-strings.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
The second statement of the definition specifies a closure criterion with a space limitation on the test string.  Given $x$ as input, do something and return a binary string.  We require the existence of some second string $y$, where $\textnormal{length} (y) = q(|x|)$, such that we can test if someFunctionRetVal$(x) == y$.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
The final clause of the definition of \textbf{NP} states that there are some inputs $x$ for which no solution matching $y$ can be found.  In the case of the clique problem, the input $x$ and test string $y$ are $n \times n$ matrices which $M$ maps to bit strings for comparison.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}



\subsection{Informal Definition of \textbf{NP-complete}}

\begin{par}
Informally, we may refer to \textbf{NP-complete} as the set of problems which are in \textbf{NP} but are possibly not in \textbf{P}.  Examples of such problems are the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT), the traveling salesman problem, and the clique problem.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
For a problem to be in \textbf{NP} but not in \textbf{P}, it must be able to validate a solution in polynomial time, yet require exponential time or worse to find a solution.  That is, the number of instructions necessary to compute a correct solution, scales on the order of $2^n$.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}



