\subsubsection{Claim}

\begin{par}
The clique problem is not in \textbf{P}.
\end{par} \vspace{1em}



\subsubsection{Proof}

\begin{par}
This was proven by the previous theorem.  The clique problem, regardless of whether the search is for all cliques or just a single clique, has a lower bound of $\Omega \left( \frac{2^n}{n} \right)$. $\blacksquare$
\end{par} \vspace{1em}

\begin{par}
Since the clique problem is in \textbf{NP-complete}, we have shown that \textbf{NP} $\neq$ \textbf{P}.
